===Etymology===
Borrowing from {{bor|en|la|Sardinia}} and {{der|en|grc|Σαρδώ}}, which in turn derive from a pre-Roman {{der|en|qfa-sub}} language, {{m|und|*sard, *shard}}. It is connected by some scholars to the name of the ''{{w|Sherden}}'' or ''Shardana'', an ethnic group amongst the {{w|Sea People}}s. A Phoenician inscription found in {{w|Nora, Italy|Nora}} and dated to the 9th century {{B.C.}} identifies the island as ''Shardan''.<ref>''The Cambridge Ancient History'' {{ISBN|0521086914}}, page 369: "In the earliest Phoenician inscription found in Sardinia, that from Nora, probably of the ninth century B.C., although it is incomplete, the name of the island appears as Shardan (be-shardan), [...]"</ref>

